Subject: Fix nested rules being dropped when a rule's @apply expands to multiple declarations

TailwindPHP v1.4.2 bug (src/apply.php): when a CSS rule's `@apply` expands to
MORE THAN ONE declaration and that same rule also contains nested child rules
that use `@apply`, every nested child of that rule is silently dropped from the
output. A single-declaration `@apply` in the parent does not trigger it.

Minimal reproduction:

    #b  { @apply mt-0 mb-0; .child { @apply block; } }   // .child is DROPPED
    #ok { @apply pl-0;      .kid   { @apply block; } }   // .kid survives

Root cause: substituteAtApply() tracks AST nodes by their integer index path
(e.g. "12.1") instead of by object identity like the TypeScript original
(packages/tailwindcss/src/apply.ts), then substitutes each parent's @apply at
its own precomputed path. The non-@utility branch substituted only the parent's
DIRECT children and deferred nested rules to their own path entry. When the
parent's `@apply` expands to N > 1 declarations, the following siblings (the
nested child rules) shift index, invalidating their tracked paths, so their own
@apply is never substituted and the child rule is discarded.

Fix (matches apply.ts semantics):
  1. Substitute every parent's @apply with a single recursive walk() over its
     subtree, so nested rules are resolved in place regardless of index shifts
     (apply.ts runs one walk() per sorted parent for both @utility and regular
     rules; the port's separate non-recursive path was the deviation).
  2. Propagate a nested @apply's dependency up to every ancestor rule that also
     uses @apply, mirroring apply.ts's walk over ctx.path(). This keeps an
     ancestor topologically sorted after any @utility its nested rules apply,
     so the now-recursive substitution never runs before a dependency is ready.

Validated against the full upstream test suite (4,075 tests OK) plus the new
regression case above.

